article.description: Kendra Wecker scored 18 points and No. 9 Kansas State beat Nebraska 89-69 Saturday for its sixth straight win.
article.headline: Cats hold Huskers to 37 percent shooting
article.linkText: K State dominates Nebraska for sixth straight win
article.story:
MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- Kansas State can't erase its only
conference loss of the season. However, the Wildcats made it easier
to accept in their second meeting with Nebraska.

Kendra Wecker scored 18 points and No. 9 Kansas State beat
Nebraska 89-69 Saturday for its sixth straight win. The Wildcats
(19-3, 10-1 Big 12) dominated early in the second half and evened
their 81-63 loss in Lincoln on Jan. 24.

"After we got our rears kicked in Lincoln we wanted to come in
with focus," Wecker said. "Early in the second half, we pushed up
the tempo and got some easy baskets. I think it kind of hit them
pretty hard."

The Wildcats led 41-26 at halftime, and made eight of their
first 10 shots of the second half to stretch their lead to 28
points within the first seven minutes of the period. Claire Coggins
scored seven points during a 17-5 run and Kansas State took its
largest lead at 64-36 with 13:19 remaining.

"That was a tough loss in Lincoln for them and they wanted to
avenge it," Nebraska coach Conni Yori said. "It's clear that they
were the aggressors."

Twiggy McIntyre had 13, Claire Coggins scored 12, and Laurie
Koehn and Nicole Ohlde each had 11 for Kansas State, winners of 30
straight at home in the regular season.

The Wildcats were 11-of-17 from 3-point range.

"When their starting lineup is on the floor, they have no
weaknesses," Yori said. "How do you guard them?"

Nebraska (16-7, 6-6) shot just 36 percent from the floor and was
2-of-17 on 3-pointers.

"Any time you can hold a Big 12 opponent to around 35-percent
you feel pretty good," Kansas State coach Deb Patterson said. "It
was almost like a mirror image of the way it was for Nebraska in
Nebraska. One of the major difference, quite frankly, is that we
just made shots."

Katie Morse led the Huskers with 14 points, and Alexa Johnson
and Chelsea Aubry each had 12.

Late in the first half, Nebraska scored five straight points to
cut Kansas State's lead to seven, but the Wildcats went on a 8-0
run to end the period.

"I guess it feels good to get the split," Morse said. "But we
really would have liked to win today. They did a lot of things
right today."
